Yes, it is possible to link notes from a repository directly to your Obsidian vault. Because an Obsidian
vault is essentially just a folder on your computer, there are several ways to integrate your repo notes 
depending on whether you want to sync them or just link to them. 

1. The Sync Method (Best for Editing)
The most common way is to turn your repository folder into an Obsidian vault or move your vault inside the
repository. This allows you to edit notes in Obsidian and have those changes trackable via Git. 

Obsidian Git Plugin: Install the Obsidian Git community plugin. This plugin lets you automatically pull,
commit, and push your notes to a remote repository (like GitHub or GitLab) directly from the Obsidian
interface. 

Setup:
Initialize your vault folder as a Git repository (or clone an existing one into your vault).
Use the plugin to set an auto-backup interval (e.g., every 5 minutes) to ensure your notes are always synced. 

2. The External Linking Method (Best for Reference)
If you don't want the notes to live inside your vault, you can link to them as external files using 
standard Markdown syntax.
Standard Link: Use the file:/// protocol followed by the absolute path to your note:
[Project Note](<file:///C:/path/to/your/repo/note.md>).
Plugins for External Files: You can use specialized plugins like External File Linker or External File
Embed and Link. These allow you to embed or link files from outside your vault more easily, often supporting
relative paths so the links don't break if you move the vault. 

